## AWS MQ  Integration With Lambda

One of the most common and powerful integrations is connecting Amazon MQ to AWS Lambda.
  This allows your serverless Lambda functions to automatically trigger and process messages as soon as they arrive in your ActiveMQ or RabbitMQ queues.

Steps:

🛠️ Integrating Amazon MQ with AWS Lambda
Prerequisites: You already have an Amazon MQ broker (ActiveMQ or RabbitMQ) running in a VPC.

Step 1: Secure Your Broker Credentials
AWS Lambda needs to authenticate with your MQ broker to read messages. Hardcoding passwords is a bad practice, so we will use AWS Secrets Manager.

Navigate to the AWS Secrets Manager console.

Click Store a new secret.

Choose Other type of secret.

In the Key/Value pairs, enter your broker credentials:

Key: username | Value: your-mq-username

Key: password | Value: your-mq-password

Click Next, name your secret (e.g., mq-broker-credentials), and save it.

UI Path: AWS Console ➡️ Secrets Manager ➡️ Store a new secret ➡️ Other type of secret

Step 2: Create the Lambda Function
Now, create the function that will process the messages.

Navigate to the AWS Lambda console.

Click Create function.

Select Author from scratch.

Name your function (e.g., ProcessMQMessages).

Choose your preferred runtime (e.g., Python 3.10 or Node.js 18.x).

Under Advanced settings, select the VPC, Subnets, and Security Groups that your Amazon MQ broker is using. (Lambda must be in the same network to reach the broker).

Click Create function.

UI Path: AWS Console ➡️ Lambda ➡️ Create function ➡️ Author from scratch ➡️ Advanced settings (VPC)

Step 3: Grant IAM Permissions to Lambda
Your Lambda function needs permission to read from Secrets Manager, connect to the VPC, and interact with Amazon MQ.

In your new Lambda function dashboard, go to the Configuration tab.

Click on Permissions, then click the Role name to open IAM.

Attach the following AWS managed policies to the role:

AWSLambdaSQSQueueExecutionRole (Provides basic VPC execution rights)

AWSLambdaMQExecutionRole (Provides rights to describe the MQ broker)

Add an inline policy granting secretsmanager:GetSecretValue for the secret you created in Step 1.

UI Path: Lambda Console ➡️ Configuration ➡️ Permissions ➡️ Execution role ➡️ Add permissions

Step 4: Add Amazon MQ as a Trigger:
 You will tell Lambda to listen to your MQ broker.

Go back to your Lambda function dashboard.

In the "Function overview" visual designer at the top, click + Add trigger.

In the trigger configuration dropdown, search for and select MQ.

Fill in the configuration details:

Broker: Select your Amazon MQ broker from the dropdown.

Batch size: Enter 10 (the number of messages Lambda will process at once).

Queue name: Enter the exact name of the queue you want to listen to (e.g., OrderQueue).

Source access configuration: Click "Add", select Basic Auth, and choose the Secrets Manager secret you created in Step 1.

Click Add.

UI Path: Lambda Console ➡️ Function overview ➡️ + Add trigger ➡️ Select MQ ➡️ Configure Batch, Queue, and Secrets

Step 5: Verify the Integration
Once the trigger is added, its status will briefly show as Creating and then switch to Enabled.

Whenever a message is pushed to your ActiveMQ or RabbitMQ OrderQueue
  AWS will automatically spin up your Lambda function,
  pass the message payload in the event object, and execute your code.
